result.execSummary:
The defendant was charged with both OWI (7th, 8th or 9th) and Operating w/ PAC (7th, 8th or 9th). The defendant was found guilty of OWI (7th, 8th or 9th) and the other charge, Operating w/ PAC (7th, 8th or 9th) was dismissed by the court.

  • Emily A Ewald was found guilty of OWI (7th, 8th or 9th), a class F felony, Wisconsin Statutes 346.63(1)(a).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes:
-Defendant is not eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program.
Defendant is eligible for the Substance Abuse Program after serving 2.5 years of initial confinement.

superMiscConds.notes: -Fine to be paid as a condition of probation.

-Costs to be paid as a condition of probation. 
-Defendant to provide DNA sample, if not yet provided, immediately if in custody otherwise within (3) business days at the Waukesha County Sheriff Department. 
-Reimbursement for Blood Draw costs to be paid/forwarded to Township of Oconomowoc Police Department.

-Submit to an AODA assessment, follow through with any treatment, counseling.  No use or possession of alcohol or illegal drugs/drug paraphernalia. Comply with random urine screens.  Maintain absolute sobriety. No use or possession of prescription drugs without a valid prescription.

-Maintain/obtain full time employment (35 hours per week.)
-Operate a motor vehicle only with a valid driver's license. 
-No new law violations. 
-Defendant to attend Victim Impact Panel. 
-If Probation/Extended Supervision is revoked and/or a prison term ordered, outstanding financial obligations shall be collected pursuant to statutory provisions, including deductions from inmate prison monies.  If discharged with outstanding financial obligations, a civil judgment shall be entered against the defendant and in favor of restitution victims and government entities for outstanding financial obligations.  Collections may include income assignment.

superTimeConds.notes: -20 hours of community services to be completed each year of extended supervision as a conditions of extended supervision. (Agencies that work with people under the influence of alcohol or drugs.)

supervisions.notes: -Ignition Interlock to be installed on every vehicle TITLED OR REGISTERED to the defendant.
